https://prez.dev/description.@value: This vocabulary lists the fundamental types of geological features that are used to define the geological framework/4D evolution of Western Australia and are relevant to the duties of the Geological Survey of Western Australia. A geological feature is a physical or conceptual feature that is hypothesized to exist coherently in the Earth and that results from geological processes (definition largely derived from SWEET ontology http://sweetontology.net/realmGeol#geologicfeature).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Concentrations of naturally occurring solid, gas, and liquid geological materials within the earth’s crust (both on and below the surface) that occur in sufficient masses or volumes to have existing or potential economic and societal value. These resources include, but are not limited to, rock, metal and non-metal mineral resources, oil, natural gas, and geothermal energy resources; and environmental resources (water and soil).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hist.@value: Definition compiled from American Geosciences Institute Glossary of Geology (5th edition).
